Multinomial logistic regression, also known as softmax regression, is a widely used machine learning classification model. It extends logistic regression to handle multiple classes, making it suitable for problems where the outcome can belong to one of three or more categories.

In this project, we will first explain the theoretical foundations and mathematical formulation of multinomial logistic regression. Following this, we will implement the model from scratch, incorporating stochastic gradient descent for optimization. We will then thoroughly test and fine-tune the model to achieve the best possible performance.

The specific task we are tackling involves classifying wines into three classes representing different cultivars from the same region in Italy. The dataset comprises 14 features, including the class variable, most of which pertain to the chemical constituents of the wine.

## The Binary Case

Before building our model and tackling the multinomial classification task, we quickly review the basics of logistic regression. Given a $(N \times M)$ data matrix $X$, the goal is to learn a vector of $N$ parameters $\omega$, such that for of a specific datapoint $x^{(i)}$, the probability that $y^{(i)} = 1$ is given by the logistic function with input $\omega^\intercal x^{(i)}$. Symbolically we have:
$$
p(y^{(i)} = 1) = \sigma(\omega^\intercal x^{(i)}) = \frac{1}{1 + e^{-\omega^\intercal x^{(i)}}}
$$

Since $y^{(i)}$ is a binary variable, we can model it as a bernoulli random variable with distribution:
$$
p(y^{(i)} \ | \  x^{(i)}, \omega) = \sigma(\omega^\intercal x^{(i)})^{y^{(i)}} \cdot (1 - \sigma(\omega^\intercal x^{(i)}))^{1 - y^{(i)}}
$$

The cost function used is then simply the negative log-likelihood of this bernoulli random variable, this is commonly known as the cross-entropy loss.

$$
J(\omega) = -\sum_{n=1}^{N}y^{(n)} \cdot \text{log}(\sigma(\omega^\intercal x^{(i)})) + (1 - y^{(n)}) \cdot \text{log}(1 - \sigma(\omega^\intercal x^{(i)}))
$$

Which simplifies to:

$$
J(\omega) = \frac{1}{N}\sum_{n=1}^{N}y^{(n)} \cdot \text{log}(1 + e^{-\omega^\intercal x^{(n)}}) + (1 - y^{(n)}) \cdot \text{log}(1 + e^{-\omega^\intercal x^{(i)}})
$$


Note that the we divide by $N$ so the scale of the loss is independent of dataset size, this makes the function better behaved during optimization. Note that this cross-entropy cost function has no analytical solution so we use gradient descent to estimate a minimum, the function is however convexe, so a global minimum should be found with gradiant descent.

<br>

## The Multinomial Case

When we are dealing with $ C > 2$ classes, we must expand the model to contain $C \times M$ parameters, $M$ parameters for each class. Given a data point $x^{(i)}$, the model will output a probability vector $\hat{y}^{(i)}$ where $\hat{y}^{(i)}_c$ is the probability that $y^{(i)} = c$. This is achieved through the softmax function.

$$
\hat{y}^{(i)} = \text{softmax}([\omega_1^\intercal x^{(i)}, \ \omega_2^\intercal x^{(i)}, \ ..., \ \omega_C^\intercal x^{(i)}]) = \bigg[\frac{e^{\omega_1^\intercal x^{(i)}}}{\sum_{c=1}^C e^{\omega_c^\intercal x^{(i)}}}, \ \frac{e^{\omega_2^\intercal x^{(i)}}}{\sum_{c=1}^C e^{\omega_c^\intercal x^{(i)}}}, \ ..., \ \frac{e^{\omega_C^\intercal x^{(i)}}}{\sum_{c=1}^C e^{\omega_c^\intercal x^{(i)}}}\bigg]
$$

Where each $\omega_i$ is a distinct $M$ parameter vector. $y^{(i)}$ is then a categorical variable with conditional distribution:

$$
p(y^{(i)} \ | \ \hat{y}^{(i)}) = \prod_{c=1}^C{\hat{y}_c^{(i)}}^{\mathbb{1}(y \ = \ c)}
$$

With log-likelihood:

$$
\ell([\omega_1, \ \omega_2, \ ..., \ \omega_c]) = \sum_{n=1}^N \sum_{c=1}^C \mathbb{1}(y^{(n)} = c)(\omega_c^\intercal x^{(n)} - \text{log} \sum_k^C e^{\omega^\intercal_k x^{(n)}})
$$
If we use one-hot encoding for labels, where $y^{(n)} \rightarrow [\mathbb{1}(y^{(n)} = 1), \ ..., \ \mathbb{1}(y^{(n)} = C)]$, and negate the above function, we get the softmax cross-entropy cost function.
$$
J(\omega) = J([\omega_1, \ \omega_2, \ ..., \ \omega_c]) = - \sum_{n=1}^N(y^{(n)\intercal}z^{(n)} - \text{log} \sum_{k=1}^C e^{z_k^{(n)}}) \ \ \ \text{with} \ \ \ z^{(n)} = \omega^\intercal x^{(n)}
$$

In practice,  we replace $\text{log} \sum_{k=1}^C e^{z_k^{(n)}}$ by $\bar{z} + \text{log} \sum_{k=1}^C e^{z_k^{(n)} - \bar{z}}$ where $\bar{z} = \text{max}_c \ z_c$ in order to prevent under/overflow and make the computation numerically stable.

<br>

## Training the Model

The above cost function has no analytical solution, we therefore use gradiant descent to find the minimizing coefficients. For that, we need the gradiant of $J$.
$$
\nabla J(\omega) = [\frac{\partial}{\partial \omega_{1,1}}J, \ ..., \ \frac{\partial}{\partial \omega_{1,M}}J, \ ..., \ \frac{\partial}{\partial \omega_{C,M}}J]
$$
Where
$$
\frac{\partial}{\partial \omega_{c,m}} J = \sum_{n=1}^N \frac{\partial J}{\partial z_c^{(n)}} \frac{\partial z_c^{(n)}}{\partial \omega_{c,m}}
= \sum_{n=1}^{N} (\hat{y}^{(n)}_c - y_c^{(n)}) x_m^{(n)}
$$
We will implement and test a few different gradiant descent algorithms, the first one being minibatch stochastic grdiant descent (SGD). The algorithm works as follows, we start with some initial parameter configuration $w^{\\{0\\}}$, and update using the rule:

$$
\omega^{\\{t + 1\\}} \leftarrow \omega^{\\{t\\}} - \alpha \nabla J_{\mathbb{B}}(\omega^{\\{t\\}})
$$

Where $\nabla J_{\mathbb{B}} = \frac{1}{|\mathbb{B}|} \sum_{n \in \mathbb{B}} \nabla J_n(\omega)$ and $\mathbb{B}$ is simply a subset of the data points in the training set, $\alpha$ is a hyperparameter known as the learning rate.

#### Momentum
To help mitigate the oscillations of minibtach SGD, we can add a momentum term, this introduces a new hyperparameter $\beta$, the algorithm then becomes:

$$
\Delta \omega^{\\{t + 1\\}} \leftarrow \beta \Delta \omega^{\\{t\\}} + (1 - \beta) \nabla J_{\mathbb{B}}(\omega^{\\{t\\}}) 
$$
$$
\omega^{\\{t + 1\\}} \leftarrow \omega^{\\{t\\}} - \alpha \Delta \omega^{\\{t\\}}
$$

#### Adagrad
Another option is to use a different learning rate for each parameter $\omega_m$, this is known as adaptive gradiant or Adagrad, it is useful when parameters are updated at different rates in which case it can accelerate convergence, the adagrad algorithm is:
$$
S_m^{\\{t + 1\\}} \leftarrow S_m^{\\{t\\}} + \bigg(\frac{\partial}{\partial \omega_m} J(\omega^{\\{t\\}})\bigg)^2
$$
$$
\omega_m^{\\{t + 1\\}} \leftarrow \omega_m^{\\{t\\}} - \frac{\alpha}{\sqrt{S_m^{\\{t + 1\\}} + \epsilon}}\frac{\partial}{\partial \omega_m} J(\omega^{\\{t\\}})
$$

#### RMSprop
Adagrad can have a problem with the learning rate decaying to 0 too quickly, this is addressed my the Root Mean Squared propagation algorithm or RMSprop, where an exponential moving average is used instead of a sum like Adagrad. The RMSprop algorithm is:
$$
S_m^{\\{t + 1\\}} \leftarrow \gamma S_m^{\\{t\\}} + (1 - \gamma)\bigg(\frac{\partial}{\partial \omega_m} J(\omega^{\\{t\\}})\bigg)^2
$$
$$
\omega_m^{\\{t + 1\\}} \leftarrow \omega_m^{\\{t\\}} - \frac{\alpha}{\sqrt{S_m^{\\{t + 1\\}} + \epsilon}}\frac{\partial}{\partial \omega_m} J(\omega^{\\{t\\}})
$$

#### Adam
Finally we have the Adaptive Moment Estimation algorithm or Adam, which combines both momentum and adaptive per-parameter learning rate, this is the default algorithm that is used in practice. The Adam algorithm is:
$$
M^{\\{t + 1\\}} \leftarrow \beta_1 M^{\\{t\\}} + (1 - \beta_1)\nabla J(\omega^{\\{t\\}})
$$
$$
S^{\\{t + 1\\}} \leftarrow \beta_2 S^{\\{t\\}} + (1 - \beta_2)\nabla J(\omega^{\\{t\\}})^2
$$
$$
\omega^{\\{t + 1\\}} \leftarrow \omega^{\\{t\\}} - \frac{\alpha}{\sqrt{\hat{S}^{\\{t + 1\\}} + \epsilon}}\hat{M}^{\\{t+1\\}}
$$
Where $\hat{M^{\\{t\\}}} = \frac{M^{\\{t\\}}}{1 - \beta_1^t}$ and $\hat{S^{\\{t\\}}} = \frac{S^{\\{t\\}}}{1 - \beta_2^t}$.

<br>

## Python Implementation

First, we implement the softmax function and a cross-entropy gradiant function which returns the gradiant given data points and coefficients, the graidant also comes with options for regularization.
```python
def softmax(z):
    z -= np.max(z)
    ans = (np.exp(z).T / (np.sum(np.exp(z),axis=1) + 1e-16))
    return ans

# Cross-entropy gradiant
def gradiant_ce(x, y, w, reg, lambdaa):
  z = np.dot(x, w.T)
  y_pred = softmax(z)
  grad = np.dot(x.T, (y_pred-y).T)/x.shape[0]   #grad is C x D (matrix)
  
  if reg == 'L2':
    grad.T[:][1:] += lambdaa * w[:][1:]

  elif reg == 'L1':
    grad.T[:][1:] += lambdaa * np.sign(w[:][1:])

  return grad.T

```

We now implement an optimizer class which will be used to run the selected gradiant descent algorithm and find coefficient values. The class let's us specify which of the specific gradiant descent implementations to use, all hyperparameters such as learning rate, mini-batch size, and momentum strength. The optimizer also implements regularization ('L1' and 'L2') and regularization strength can be specified.

```python
# Implementation can be:
# ['stochastic', 'momentum', 'adagrad', 'rmsprop', 'adam']
class GradiantDescent:

  def __init__(self, learning_rate = 0.001, max_iters = 1e4, epsilon = 1e-8,
                implementation = 'stochastic', batch_size = None, momentum = None,
               record_history = False, regularization = None, lambdaa = 0.0):    
                                           # For adam momentum should be a list of 2 numbers, batch_size always required unless implementation = default
                                           # If batch_size is unspecified and implementation = 'stochastic' we get full batch gradiant descent
        self.learning_rate = learning_rate
        self.max_iters = max_iters
        self.epsilon = epsilon
        self.implementation = implementation
        self.batch_size = batch_size
        self.momentum = momentum
        self.record_history = record_history
        if record_history:
          self.w_history = []
        self.regularization = regularization
        self.lambdaa = lambdaa

  def run(self, x, y, w, grad_fn):


    if self.batch_size == None:
      self.batch_size = len(x)

    x_batch = x
    y_batch = y

    m = np.zeros(w.shape) #first moment
    s = np.zeros(w.shape) #second moment
    grad = np.inf
    t = 1

    while np.linalg.norm(grad) > self.epsilon and t < self.max_iters:

      if self.batch_size != len(x):
         random_indices = np.random.randint(0, len(x) - 1, self.batch_size)
         x_batch = x[random_indices]
         if y.shape[0] == 3:
          y_batch = y[:,random_indices]
         else:
          y_batch = y[random_indices]

      if self.record_history:
        self.w_history.append(w)

      grad = grad_fn(x_batch, y_batch, w, self.regularization, self.lambdaa)

      match self.implementation:

        case 'stochastic':
            w = w - self.learning_rate * grad
            t += 1

        case 'momentum':
            delta_w = (self.momentum * delta_w) + (1 - self.momentum)*grad
            w = w - self.learning_rate * delta_w
            t += 1

        case 'adagrad':
            s = s + grad**2
            w = w - (self.learning_rate/np.sqrt(s + self.epsilon)) * grad
            t += 1

        case 'rmsprop':
            s = self.momentum*s + (1 - self.momentum)*grad
            w = w - (self.learning_rate/np.sqrt(s + self.epsilon)) * grad
            t += 1

        case 'adam':
            b1, b2 = self.momentum[0], self.momentum[1]
            m = b1*m + (1 - b1)*grad
            s = b2*s + (1 - b2)*grad**2
            w = w - (self.learning_rate/(np.sqrt((s/(1-b2**t)) + self.epsilon))) * (m/(1 - b1**t))
            t += 1

    return w
```
We can now implement an actual logistic regression class along with a function that performs one-hot encoding.

```python
def oh_encoding(y):
  y_ohe = np.zeros([3, len(y)])
  for i in range(3):
    for j in range(len(y)):
      if y[j] == i+1:
        y_ohe[i,j] = 1
  return y_ohe.T

class LogisticRegression:

  def fit(self, x, y, optimizer):

    x = x.values
    y = y.values
    x = np.column_stack([x,np.ones(x.shape[0])]) #Add bias

    perm = np.random.permutation(len(x))  #Shuffle data
    x = x[perm]
    y = y[perm]

    # One-hot encoding labels
    y = oh_encoding(y)
    w0 = np.zeros([3, x.shape[1]]) #3 classes

    self.w = optimizer.run(x, y.T, w0, gradiant_ce)

  def predict(self, x):

    x = x.values
    x = np.column_stack([x,np.ones(x.shape[0])]) #Add bias
    z = self.w@x.T
    for i in range(z.shape[1]):
      z[:,i] = z[:,i] - np.max(z, axis = 1)
    y_pred = softmax(z).T
    return np.argmax(y_pred, axis=0) + 1
```
## Evaluation Metrics

We have a couple of options to evaluate the performance of a classification model like logistic regression. The most straightforward of these is accuracy, defined as:
$$
\text{Accuracy} = \frac{\text{Correct Predictions}}{\text{Total Predictions}}
$$
Will use three other performance metrics that apply on a per-class basis, these are:
$$
 \text{Precision} = \frac{\text{True Positives}}{\text{Total Predicted Positives}} \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \
 \text{Recall} = \frac{\text{True Positives}}{\text{Total Actual Positives}} \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \
 \text{F1-score} = 2 \cdot \frac{\text{Precision} \cdot \text{Recall}}{\text{Precision} + \text{Recall}}
 $$
Accuracy measures the overall correctness of the model, while precision focuses on the accuracy of positive predictions and recall on the model's ability to identify all actual positives. The F1-score balances precision and recall, providing a single metric that considers both false positives and false negatives.

Since we do not distinguish between types of errors, we will primarily focus on optimizing accuracy. We will use 5-fold cross-validation to ensure robust evaluation and average the metrics across classes for our experiments.

Below is the python implementation of these metrics.

```python
# Accuracy
def accuracy(y, y_pred):
  true_pred = sum(1 for pred, true in zip(y, y_pred) if pred == true)
  return round(true_pred/len(y),4)

# Precision
def precision(y, y_pred, classes):

  precisions = []

  for cls in classes:
    t_p = sum(1 for pred, true in zip(y_pred, y) if pred == cls and true == cls)
    f_p = sum(1 for pred, true in zip(y_pred, y) if pred == cls and true != cls)
    precisions.append(t_p / (t_p + f_p))

  return precisions

# Recall
def recall(y, y_pred, classes):

  recalls = []

  for cls in classes:
    t_p = sum(1 for pred, true in zip(y_pred, y) if pred == cls and true == cls)
    f_n = sum(1 for pred, true in zip(y_pred, y) if pred != cls and true == cls)
    recalls.append(t_p / (t_p + f_n))

  return recalls

# F1-score
def f1_score(y, y_pred, classes):

  precisions = precision(y, y_pred, classes)
  recalls = recall(y, y_pred, classes)

  return [2 * (p * r)/(p + r) for p, r in zip(precisions, recalls)]
```
For this classifiaction task, we treat all classes in the same way, therefore, for our experiments, we will present all 4 metrics but we will average precision, recall, and f1-score across classes and folds. Accuracy will only be averaged across folds. The below python functions compute and display the metrics as discussed.

```python
def lgstc_reg_metrics(y, y_pred, verbose = False):

  classes = [1,2,3]

  acc = accuracy(y, y_pred)

  precisions = precision(y, y_pred, classes)
  precision_mean = np.mean(precisions)
  precisions.append(precision_mean)
  precisions.insert(0, 'Precision')

  recalls = recall(y, y_pred, classes)
  recall_mean = np.mean(recalls)
  recalls.append(recall_mean)
  recalls.insert(0, 'Recall')

  f1 = f1_score(y, y_pred, classes)
  f1_mean = np.mean(f1)
  f1.append(f1_mean)
  f1.insert(0, 'F1-score')

  if verbose:
    print(f'Accuracy: {acc * 100}%\n')
    table = [precisions, recalls, f1]
    print(tabulate(table, headers = ['Metric', 'Class 1', 'Class 2', 'Class 3',
                                     'Average']))

  return [acc, precision_mean, recall_mean, f1_mean]


def kfold_cross_validation(data, k, model, optimizer = None, verbose = True, metric : Callable = lgstc_reg_metrics):

  metrics_test = []
  data = data.sample(frac=1).reset_index(drop = True) #Shuffle data
  fold_size = len(data) // k

  for i in range(k):
    test = data.iloc[i*fold_size:(i+1)*fold_size]
    train = pd.concat([data.iloc[:i*fold_size], data.iloc[(i+1)*fold_size:]],
                      axis = 0)

    x_train, y_train = train.iloc[:,:-1], train.iloc[:,-1]
    x_test, y_test = test.iloc[:,:-1], test.iloc[:,-1]

    model.fit(x_train, y_train, optimizer)
    pred_test = model.predict(x_test)
    metrics_test.append(metric(y_test, pred_test))

  avg_acc = np.mean(metrics_test[:][0])
  avg_precision = np.mean(metrics_test[:][1])
  avg_recall = np.mean(metrics_test[:][2])
  avg_f1 = np.mean(metrics_test[:][3])

  if verbose:
    print('5-fold cross-validation with metrics averaged across classes and '
          'folds:\n')

    table = prettytable.PrettyTable()
    table.field_names = ['Accuracy', 'Precision', 'Recall', 'F1-score']
    table.add_row([avg_acc, avg_precision, avg_recall, avg_f1])
    print(table)

  return avg_acc, avg_precision, avg_recall, avg_f1
```

## Testing and Experimentation

In this section we will thouroughly test the model using the previously discussed metrics and methods. We will apply modifcation to the data, model, and optimizer and study the impact on perfrormnace, and speed of convergence.

### Normalization

First and foremort, we analyse the impact of data normalization, some features are of greatly different scales, which can negatively impact logistic regression performance, we therefore expect a significant improvemnt from normalization. We will use standard stochastic gradient descent with a learning rate of $10^{-5}$.

The following code defines a function that normalizes the non-target features and performs the test
```python
def normalize(data):
  x, y = data.iloc[:,:-1], data.iloc[:,-1]
  x_n = x.copy()
  for col in x_n:
    x_n[col] = (x_n[col] - x_n[col].mean())/x_n[col].std()
  return x_n.join(y)

#Unormalized
print('Unormalized:\n')
model = LogisticRegression()
optimizer = GradiantDescent(implementation = 'stochastic', learning_rate = 1e-5)
_ = kfold_cross_validation(wine_data, 5, model, optimizer, verbose = True)
print('\n')

#Normalized
print('Normalized:\n')
wine_data_normal = normalize(wine_data)
model = LogisticRegression()
optimizer = GradiantDescent(implementation = 'stochastic', learning_rate = 1e-5)
_ = kfold_cross_validation(wine_data_normal, 5, model, optimizer, verbose = True)
```

### Learning Rate

In the previous section, we found that the learning rate has little impact on model performance after 10,000 iterations when using the SGD optimizer. However, it is still worthwhile to study the impact of learning rate on convergence speed. Below, we graph the cost curves of the algorithm at various learning rates to observe their effects on convergence.

```python
fig = plt.subplot()
learning_rates = [0.5, 0.1, 0.001, 0.0001, 0.00001]
for alpha in learning_rates:
  optimizer = GradiantDescent(learning_rate = alpha, max_iters = 100000, batch_size = 64, record_history = True)
  model = LogisticRegression()
  model.fit(x_train, y_train, optimizer)
  x_train = np.column_stack([x_train ,np.ones(x_train.shape[0])])

```

### Batch Size

We now study the effect of batch size on the convergence of the optimizer. Batch size is an important hyperparameter in the training process as it determines the number of samples used in each iteration of the optimizer. Smaller batch sizes can provide more frequent updates and lead to faster convergence, but they may also introduce more noise in the gradient estimates. Larger batch sizes, on the other hand, offer more stable gradient estimates but might converge more slowly.

The following code graphs the training loss for all 20,000 iterations at different batch sizes:

``` python
test_train = train_test_split(wine_data_normal, 0.8)
train, test = test_train[0], test_train[1]

x_train, y_train = train.iloc[:,:-1], train.iloc[:,-1]
x_test, y_test = test.iloc[:,:-1], test.iloc[:,-1]

fig = plt.subplot()
batch_sizes = [8, 16, 32, 64, 128]
for bs in batch_sizes:
  optimizer = GradiantDescent(learning_rate = 0.5, max_iters = 20000, batch_size = bs, record_history = True)
  model = LogisticRegression()
  model.fit(x_train, y_train, optimizer)
  x_train = np.column_stack([x_train ,np.ones(x_train.shape[0])])
  y_train_oh = oh_encoding(y_train)
  plt.plot(range(19999) , cost_history(x_train, y_train_oh, optimizer.w_history),
           label = f'batch size = {bs}')
plt.legend()

fig.spines[['right', 'top']].set_visible(False)
fig.legend(frameon = False)
```

We find that a relatively small batch size of 16 results in the fastest convergence which is also stable (little volatility in training loss), we will therefore proceed with a batch size of 16 for further experiments.
### L1 Regularization
L1 regularization, also known as lasso regularization, adds a linear L1 penalty term to the cost function. This approach is equivalent to finding the maximum posteriori with a Laplace prior. The cost function then becomes:

$$
J(\omega) = - \sum_{n=1}^N(y^{(n)\intercal}z^{(n)} - \text{log} \sum_{k=1}^C e^{z_k^{(n)}}) + \lambda ||\omega||_1
$$

The partial derivative of any one parameter $w_{c,m}$ then simply becomes:

$$
\frac{\partial}{\partial \omega_{c,m}} J = \sum_{n=1}^{N} (\hat{y}^{(n)}_c - y_c^{(n)}) x_m^{(n)} + \lambda \cdot \text{sign}(\omega\_{c,m})
$$

L1 regularization tends to create sparser models, effectively performing feature selection and mitigating overfitting. We have already incorporated it in our functions. The following code tests the model with L1 regularization at different strengths, from 0 (no regularization) to 0.1 (strong regularization).

```python
accuracies = []
strengths = [0, 0.001, 0.01, 0.05, 0.1]

for value in strengths:
  optimizer = GradiantDescent(learning_rate = 0.5, max_iters = 20000, batch_size = 16,
                              regularization = 'L1', lambdaa = value)
  model = LogisticRegression()
  accuracies.append(round(kfold_cross_validation(wine_data_normal, 5, model, optimizer, verbose = False)[0], 2))

headers = ['Lambda', 'Accuracy']
print(tabulate(zip(strengths, accuracies), headers = headers))
```
Which outputs:
```
  Lambda    Accuracy
--------  ----------
   0            0.97
   0.001        0.9
   0.01         0.79
   0.05         0.73
   0.1          0.74
```
We conclude that there is no benefit in incorporating L1 regularization into our model, as it seems to strictly decrease performance in terms of accuracy.

### L2 Regularization

L2 regularization, also known as ridge regularization, adds a quadratic L2 penalty term to the cost function. This approach helps prevent overfitting by penalizing large coefficient values. The cost function then becomes:

$$
J(\omega) = - \sum_{n=1}^N(y^{(n)\intercal}z^{(n)} - \text{log} \sum_{k=1}^C e^{z_k^{(n)}}) + \frac{\lambda}{2} ||\omega||_2^2
$$

The partial derivative of any one parameter $w_{c,m}$ then simply becomes:

$$
\frac{\partial}{\partial \omega_{c,m}} J = \sum_{n=1}^{N} (\hat{y}^{(n)}_c - y_c^{(n)}) x_m^{(n)} + \lambda \cdot \omega\_{c,m}
$$

L2 regularization tends to create more stable models by shrinking the coefficients, which can mitigate overfitting. We have already incorporated it in our functions. The following code tests the model with L2 regularization at different strengths, from 0 (no regularization) to 0.1 (strong regularization).

```python
accuracies = []
strengths = [0, 0.001, 0.01, 0.05, 0.1]

for value in strengths:
  optimizer = GradiantDescent(learning_rate = 0.5, max_iters = 20000, batch_size = 64,
                              regularization = 'L2', lambdaa = value)
  model = LogisticRegression()
  accuracies.append(round(kfold_cross_validation(wine_data_normal, 5, model, optimizer, verbose = False)[0], 2))

headers = ['Lambda', 'Accuracy']
print(tabulate(zip(strengths, accuracies), headers = headers))
```
Which outputs:
```
  Lambda    Accuracy
--------  ----------
   0            0.94
   0.001        0.71
   0.01         0.75
   0.05         0.6
   0.1          0.65
```
Again, we find that there is no benefit in incorporating L2 regularization into our model, it strictly decreases performance in terms of accuracy.

### Final Model
Based on our testing, the optimal configuration for the logistic regression model includes a learning rate of 0.5 and a batch size of 16, utilizing stochastic gradient descent. The following code trains this model for 40,000 iterations and evaluates it using 5-fold cross-validation:
```python
optimizer = GradiantDescent(learning_rate = 0.5, max_iters = 40000, batch_size = 16)
model = LogisticRegression()
print("5-fold Cross validation on final model (learning rate = 0.5), (batch size = 16), metrics averaged across folds and classes\n")
```
